        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 24:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " : “they found me,” indeed, as they have said, but ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "οὐ μετὰ ὄχλου κ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "τ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "λ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".; a direct answer to the charge of profaning the Temple: he had gone there for worship and sacrifice, “then how did I profane it?” Chrys., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Hom.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", .—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἡγνισμένον",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ": the expression is generally taken to refer to the offerings involved in the association with the vow, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 21:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", but it may also include other acts of worship and purification in the Temple.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "τινὲς",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ": in A.V. the word is simply referred to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "εὗρον",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and there is no difficulty; but if we insert ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "δέ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " after it (see critical note). R.V. renders “but ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "there were",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " certain Jews from Asia,” etc. The sentence breaks off, and the speaker makes no direct reference to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 21:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", but implies that these Asiatic Jews should have been present to accuse him if they had any accusation to make—their absence was in the prisoner’s favour; “the passage as it stands (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", with this break) is instinct with life, and seems to exhibit the abruptness so characteristic of the Pauline Epistles,” ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "cf.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 26:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", see Page’s note ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "in loco",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Others take ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "δέ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " though less forcibly as more strictly in opposition to the preceding words, meaning that his accusers had not found him as they alleged, and as Tertullus alleged, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 24:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", but that certain Jews of Asia had found him. Hackett retains ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "δέ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and sees in the words a retort of the charge of riot upon the true authors of it: “but certain Jews from Asia”—it is they who excited a tumult, not I; the verb could be omitted, a true picture of the Apostle’s earnestness, because so readily suggested from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "θορύβου",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", but this interpretation seems hardly borne out by the context.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
